==================================================================
CHAPTER 9: LIMITATIONS
==================================================================

9.1 Dataset Limitation
The majority of experiments were performed on MNIST. While appropriate for method development and controlled benchmarking, broader validation is needed on more complex and realistic datasets.

9.2 Hyperparameter Breadth vs Depth
Multiple parameter combinations were explored; however, exhaustive hyperparameter optimization for every strategy was not completed due to time and compute constraints.

9.3 Method Trade-offs
Some robust/fairness-oriented methods intentionally prioritize update quality and participation control, which can reduce absolute average test accuracy compared to less restrictive aggregation.

9.4 System Constraints
Large-scale encrypted FL simulations were not executed in this phase due to added computational and implementation complexity.


==================================================================
CHAPTER 10: FUTURE WORK AND HOMOMORPHIC ENCRYPTION ROADMAP
==================================================================

10.1 Strategic Direction
The next major extension is homomorphic encryption (HE)-enabled federated aggregation, where client updates are encrypted before transmission and aggregated without exposing plaintext updates at the server.

10.2 Work Prepared in Current Phase
The following HE-related milestones were completed in preparation for implementation:
- End-to-end integration blueprint finalized.
- Component boundaries for encryption, aggregation, and decryption defined.
- Method-compatibility mapping completed for robust FL variants.
- Evaluation plan drafted for privacy-performance benchmarking.

10.3 Planned Implementation Steps
1. Select and integrate suitable HE primitives for vector/tensor aggregation.
2. Implement client-side encryption of model updates.
3. Implement encrypted server-side aggregation workflow.
4. Implement secure key management and controlled decryption path.
5. Validate functional correctness against plain FL baseline.
6. Benchmark runtime, communication, and memory overhead.

10.4 Validation and Benchmarking Plan
- Accuracy preservation vs non-encrypted baseline
- Latency and throughput measurements per round
- Communication size growth due to ciphertext expansion
- Scalability under different client counts and update dimensions
- Sensitivity analysis for robust methods under encryption overhead

10.5 Expected Deliverables
- HE-integrated FL prototype
- Comparative technical report (Plain FL vs HE-FL)
- Deployment recommendations based on overhead-accuracy trade-offs


==================================================================
CHAPTER 11: CONCLUSION
==================================================================

This internship delivered a comprehensive federated learning experimentation framework with strong emphasis on robustness, adaptivity, and client-level behavior analysis. The implemented methods and resulting evidence demonstrate that practical FL system performance depends not only on average accuracy but also on how client heterogeneity is managed during aggregation.

The work produced a clear comparative understanding of baseline, rejection-based, deviation-based, and adaptive strategies in high-client-count settings. In addition, the project now has a well-defined privacy extension path through homomorphic encryption integration planning. The completed engineering foundation, organized outputs, and chapter-level documentation position this work for seamless continuation into secure FL implementation.


